message.content:
41fx | It would be most unfortunate if the High Court of Australia, or indeed other Australian courts, were to respond to the debate which has followed the Mabo decision by abdicating or curtailing their legitimate creative functions, returning the courts to a less creative role. Such an outcome would remit the common law of Australia to a condition of stagnancy, inhibiting the necessary correction of injustices by the courts in the daily performance of their charter.
7um8 | Views may legitimately differ about whether, in the particular matter of native title in Australia, the judges of the High Court would have been wiser to stay their hands and leave reform to Parliament. But my own assessment is that history will treat the decision kindly. As it will the judges who made it.
